{
  "step": 4,
  "title": "The Friction Ladder",
  "startFrame": 4771,
  "endFrame": 6942,
  "componentPath": "src/visuals/Generated_TheFrictionLadder.tsx",
  "transcriptSegment": "But neuroscientists studying digital addiction found one technique that actually breaks this cycle. It's called the Friction Ladder, and it works by deliberately adding delay between the trigger and the reward. Instead of banning A I completely, which always fails, you create increasing levels of resistance.\n\nHere's how it works in practice. When you hit a coding problem, you don't immediately reach for A I. You set a five-minute timer and force yourself to think through the problem first. Just five minutes. Most of the time, you'll solve it yourself before the timer goes off. When you do need to use A I after the timer, you get the solution plus a small sense of accomplishment for trying first.\n\nAfter a week of five-minute delays, you increase it to fifteen minutes. Then thirty minutes. Eventually, you're doing full hour-long coding sessions without any A I assistance. Your brain literally rewires itself during this process. The dopamine pathways that were firing for A I anticipation start firing for problem-solving instead.",
